iews, Biney explores the complexities of the social, economic, and cultural adaptation of this group, the difficult moral choices they have to make in order to survive, and the tensions that exist within their faith community. Most notably, through his compelling research Biney shows that such congregations are more than mere "ethnic enclaves," or safe havens from American social and cultural values. Rather, they help maintain the essential balance between cultural acclimation and ethnic preservation needed for these new citizens to flourish.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aGhanaian AmericansxReligionxNew York (State)xNew York. 0aGhanaian AmericanszNew York (State)zNew YorkxReligion. 4aAfrica. 4aAfrican. 4aAmerica. 4aBiney. 4aChurch. 4aFrom. 4aGhana. 4aMoses. 4aPCGNY. 4aPresbyterian. 4aYork. 4acongregation. 4afull-scale. 4aimmigrant. 4alook. 4aoffers. 4arare. 7aRELIGION / Christianity / Presbyterian.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNYUP Backlist 2000-2013z978311070644440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814789810423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780814789810.jpg  a978-3-11-070644-4  NYUP Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK